## Kubernetes Cluster Architecture

Kubernetes follows a **cluster architecture**.

A **cluster** means a **group of servers (machines) working together**.

In a Kubernetes cluster there are two main types of nodes:

```
1. Control Plane (Master Node)
2. Worker Nodes
```

The **control plane manages the cluster**, while **worker nodes run the applications**.

---

# Kubernetes Cluster Structure

```
Kubernetes Cluster
        |
        |
  ----------------------
  |                    |
Control Plane      Worker Nodes
(Master Node)      (Application Nodes)
```

The **Control Plane** manages the cluster and schedules workloads.

The **Worker Nodes** run the actual application containers.

---

# Kubernetes Cluster Components

## 1 Control Plane (Master Node)

The **Control Plane** is responsible for managing the Kubernetes cluster.

It contains the following components:

```
API Server
Scheduler
Controller Manager
ETCD
```

### API Server

The **API Server** is the **entry point of the Kubernetes cluster**.

All communication with the Kubernetes cluster happens through the API Server.

When a user or developer sends a request using **kubectl**, the request goes to the API Server.

Example:

```
kubectl create deployment my-app
```

The API Server receives the request and processes it.

---

### ETCD

**ETCD** is the **internal database of Kubernetes**.

It stores all cluster information such as:

```
Cluster configuration
Application deployments
Service details
Node information
Pod status
```

When a request is received by the API Server, the request information is stored in **ETCD with a pending status**.

---

### Scheduler

The **Scheduler** is responsible for assigning workloads to worker nodes.

It checks for **pending tasks in ETCD** and decides **which worker node should run the task**.

Example:

```
New Pod Request
        ↓
Scheduler identifies a suitable worker node
        ↓
Pod is scheduled on that worker node
```

The scheduler selects nodes based on:

```
CPU availability
Memory availability
Node health
Resource requirements
```

---

### Controller Manager

The **Controller Manager** ensures that the cluster is running in the **desired state**.

It continuously checks whether the system is working as expected.

Example:

If Kubernetes expects **3 pods running** but only **2 are running**, the Controller Manager will create a **new pod automatically**.

Responsibilities include:

```
Monitoring cluster state
Ensuring desired number of pods
Handling node failures
Maintaining system stability
```

---

# Worker Node Components

Worker nodes are responsible for **running the actual applications**.

Each worker node contains the following components:

```
Kubelet
Kube Proxy
Container Runtime
Pods
Containers
```

---

## Kubelet

**Kubelet** is called the **Node Agent**.

It runs on every worker node and communicates with the Control Plane.

Responsibilities of Kubelet:

```
Receive instructions from control plane
Create pods on the worker node
Monitor containers
Report node status back to control plane
```

The Scheduler identifies worker nodes using **Kubelet information**.

---

## Kube Proxy

**Kube Proxy** is responsible for **network communication inside the Kubernetes cluster**.

It ensures communication between:

```
Pods
Nodes
Services
```

It manages networking rules and ensures traffic is routed correctly.

---

## Container Runtime

The **Container Runtime** is responsible for running containers.

Common container runtimes include:

```
Docker
Containerd
CRI-O
```

In many setups, **Docker Engine** is used to run containers inside Kubernetes.

---

## Pods

In Kubernetes, containers are not created directly.

Containers are created inside a **Pod**.

A **Pod** is the **smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes**.

Example:

```
Pod
 ├── Container 1
 └── Container 2
```

A pod may contain **one or more containers**.

Pods share:

```
Network
Storage
IP Address
```

Important Note:

```
In Kubernetes everything is represented as a POD.
```

Applications are always deployed inside pods.

---

# Kubernetes Cluster Communication Flow

The request flow inside Kubernetes works like this:

```
Developer
   |
   v
kubectl CLI
   |
   v
API Server
   |
   v
ETCD (stores request)
   |
   v
Scheduler
   |
   v
Worker Node (via Kubelet)
   |
   v
Pod Created
   |
   v
Container Running
```

---

# Kubernetes Cluster Setup Options

There are multiple ways to set up a Kubernetes cluster.

## 1 Minikube

Minikube is used for **local practice and learning**.

Characteristics:

```
Single node cluster
Runs on local machine
Used for development and testing
```

Example usage:

```
minikube start
```

---

## 2 Kubeadm Cluster

Kubeadm is used to create a **self-managed Kubernetes cluster**.

In this setup, the user is responsible for:

```
Cluster installation
Node configuration
Networking
Security
Maintenance
```

This approach gives **full control over the cluster**.

---

## 3 Provider Managed Cluster

Cloud providers offer **managed Kubernetes services**.

In this setup, the cloud provider manages the control plane and infrastructure.

Examples:

```
AWS EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service)
Azure AKS (Azure Kubernetes Service)
GCP GKE (Google Kubernetes Engine)
```

Benefits:

```
Easy setup
Automatic upgrades
High availability
Managed infrastructure
```

Note:

```
Managed Kubernetes services are chargeable.
```

---

# Summary

Kubernetes uses a **cluster architecture** to manage containerized applications.

```
Kubernetes Cluster
     |
     |
 ---------------------
 |                   |
Control Plane      Worker Nodes
```

Control Plane responsibilities:

```
API Server
Scheduler
Controller Manager
ETCD
```

Worker Node responsibilities:

```
Kubelet
Kube Proxy
Container Runtime
Pods
Containers
```

Workflow summary:

```
kubectl → API Server → ETCD → Scheduler → Worker Node → Pod → Container
```

This architecture allows Kubernetes to provide:

```
Scalability
High Availability
Self Healing
Automated Container Management
```
